Fourier Transform



A Fourier transform is a very useful tool to extract the component sine waves in a mixed signal.

For example, a square wave is made up of multiple sine waves. Its Fourier expansion goes something like


﻿sin(x)+13sin(3∗x)+15sin(5∗x)...sin(x) + \frac{1}{3}sin(3*x) +\frac{1}{5}sin(5*x) ...sin(x)+​3​​1​​sin(3∗x)+​5​​1​​sin(5∗x)...﻿


So if we take a Fourier transform of this, we will see a peak at the input frequency (e.g. 1000), the next peak will be at 3000 but with 1/3 amplitude,.. and so on.

There is a peak at 0 because our input square wave is from 0-5 volts and is not centered around 0. So the peak at 0 represents the DC Offset. Try inputting SQ1 into A1 via a capacitor (to block DC) and observe the change in the FFT


For a pure sine wave, you will get a single peak


Exercise


Change the input channel to MIC, and connect a microphone between MIC and GND. Now whistle into the mic and run the code. Mix different people whistling together into the mic and observe the plot
